      {
        "id": 3034119,
        "name": "John Milliken",
        "username": "John_Milliken",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/54ee81/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2020-11-25T11:27:38.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"165933\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>Any comparison or contrast to Ramonet and Niellon?</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>There are others with a lot more experience than me, but based on the few bottles I\u2019ve had (2014s and 2015s), I\u2019ve found Ramonet\u2019s reds to also be light, focused and precise.  Curious whether this is a Chassagne thing or a function of them both being better known for their whites (or just a coincidence).  The Ramonets have been more towards the red fruit end of the spectrum, and didn\u2019t show any of the stem / whole cluster influences that are prominent in the Moreaus.</p>\n<p>I haven\u2019t tried Niellon, but it sounds like I should.</p>",
        "post_number": 5,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 7,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-03T23:46:33.259Z",
        "reply_count": 0,
